  <span id="freeText5216766423811621643" style="display:none">➳ <b>3 1/2 stars</b><br><br><i>Let’s Talk About Love</i> is really sweet and heart-warming, but I felt like something was missing? I need a little bit more than just the main character Alice <i>ace</i>ing that whole dating thing to make me <i>really</i> like a book. (rtc)<br><br><a href="https://sprinklesofdreams.wordpress.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Blog</a> | <a href="https://www.bloglovin.com/blogs/sprinkles-dreams-19449885" rel="nofollow noopener">Bloglovin’</a> | <a href="https://www.instagram.com/sprinklesofdreamsx/" rel="nofollow noopener">Instagram</a> | <a href="http://sprinklesofdreams.tumblr.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Tumblr</a> | <a href="http://twitter.com/sprnklsofdreams" rel="nofollow noopener">Twitter</a><br><br>*<br><br><b>LOOK AT THE TAGLINE, GUYS!! I’m sold (on the pun &amp; this book).</b><br><br>Also, who wants to take a minute to appreciate the diversity in this book with me; we have a Black bi- (or pan)-romantic asexual female main character, the love interest is Japanese, and in addition to the queer rep, there is also Latina and Filipino rep.<br><br><blockquote>
