<span id="freeTextContainer875384968448013492">&quot;A&quot; is for Asexual Alice! This book was truly amazing! Alice was goofy, awkward and such an overthinker. Her character was relatable and loveable. At times she could be whiny and dramatic. But I still loved that about her because it made her that much more realistic. <br/><br/>Black queer woman? ✔<br/>Realistic, respectful representation? ✔<br/>Interesting characters and plot? ✔<br/>Realistic rep of friendship? ✔<br/><br/>This book was fun, adorable and informative. It briefly touched on certain cultural issues, both from a black</span>
  <span id="freeText875384968448013492" style="display:none">"A" is for Asexual Alice! This book was truly amazing! Alice was goofy, awkward and such an overthinker. Her character was relatable and loveable. At times she could be whiny and dramatic. But I still loved that about her because it made her that much more realistic. <br /><br />Black queer woman? ✔<br />Realistic, respectful representation? ✔<br />Interesting characters and plot? ✔<br />Realistic rep of friendship? ✔<br /><br />This book was fun, adorable and informative. It briefly touched on certain cultural issues, both from a black and Japanese standpoint. AND it has a black woman ON. THE. COVER! Being beautiful, carefree and happy WITH her afro! Ahhh! I am swooning over all this beautiful representation! <br /><br />♥️It even has an ace of hearts on the binding! ♥️</span>
